TIRANA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Technical Committee of Experts advising the government of Albania on the coronavirus pandemic said on Friday that the epidemiological situation in the country was "stable" and therefore the ban on mass gatherings would be lifted. The decision was announced jointly by the head of the committee and Deputy Health Minister Mira Rakacolli. The committee has "decided to lift the restrictions on gatherings of more than 50 people and remove the 30 percent capacity limit in theaters, cinemas, stadiums and other indoor venues," Rakacolli told journalists. According to Rakacolli, travelers arriving in the country will still be required to present a vaccination certificate, a negative PCR (polymerase chain reaction) test taken 72 hours before arrival in Albania or proof of recovery from COVID-19. Albania currently has 480 active coronavirus cases, including 16 hospitalized patients. On Friday, the Health Ministry reported 82 new cases, bringing the total number of confirmed infections in the country to 273,759, with 267,787 recoveries and 3,492 fatalities. The vaccination campaign in Albania is underway. To date, over 2.76 million shots have been administered.  â– 